Projections and Coordinate Reference Systems (CRS)

Often difficult part of workign with spatial data

GCS = geographic coordinate systems based on spherical earth models

PCS = projected coordinate system Takes sphere and maps it onto a flat surface Certain projections are better depending on where you are on the earth (middle is most accurate, edges stretched)

Point data

sf is mainly for vector based data (poly-lines, polygons, point data)

moving away from rgdal because sf is easier to work with

sf vignettes to help you learn to use

st_read to read in data brings in everything as a dataframe and the geometry is its own geometry in a list

df_locs<- read_csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/ryanpeek/mapping_in_R/master/data/hotsprings_CA.csv")

#Need to add headers to columns

df_locs <-df_locs %>% 
  set_names(nm = c("State", "Lat", "Lon", "Spring_name", "Temp_C", "Temp_F", "Area", "USGS_Quad"))

glimpse(df_locs)
## Observations: 304
## Variables: 8
## $ State       <chr> "CA", "CA", "CA", "CA", "CA", "CA", "CA", "CA", "C...
## $ Lat         <dbl> 38.802, 38.767, 41.534, 36.045, 41.670, 36.036, 40...
## $ Lon         <dbl> 122.810, 122.748, 120.078, 117.769, 120.206, 117.8...
## $ Spring_name <chr> "THE \r\n      GEYSERS", "LITTLE \r\n      GEYSERS...
## $ Temp_C      <chr> "214", "210", "208", "207", "207", "207", "205", "...
## $ Temp_F      <chr> "101", "99", "98", "97", "97", "97", "96", "96", "...
## $ Area        <chr> "SANTA ROSA", "SANTA ROSA", "ALTURAS", "DEATH VALL...
## $ USGS_Quad   <chr> "THE GEYSERS 7.5", "(WHISPERING PINES 7.5)", "CEDA...
#Longitude should be negative

df_locs <- df_locs %>% 
  mutate("Lon" = -Lon)

#Make temperature numberic

df_locs <- df_locs %>% 
  mutate_at(.vars = c("Temp_C", "Temp_F"), .funs = as.numeric) 
## Warning in evalq(as.numeric(Temp_C), <environment>): NAs introduced by
## coercion
## Warning in evalq(as.numeric(Temp_F), <environment>): NAs introduced by
## coercion
# make it spatial

df_locs_sf <- st_as_sf(df_locs, 
                       coords = c("Lon", "Lat"),# or = c(3,2) col numbers
                      remove = F,
                      crs = 4326) #coordinate reference system (numbers for each projection), This is a WGS84 GCS

Making a map

library(mapview)
mapview(df_locs_sf)
#Crop to points in Tulare county
#install.packages("USAboundaries")
library(USAboundaries)

#us_boundaries, us_cities, us_counties, us_states

tulare <- us_counties(resolution = "low", states = "CA") %>% 
  filter(name == "Tulare")

mapview(tulare) + mapview(df_locs_sf) #layers like ggplot2

###intersect the hotsprings with Tulare Co

tuls_hs <- st_intersection(df_locs_sf, tulare)
## although coordinates are longitude/latitude, st_intersection assumes that they are planar
## Warning: attribute variables are assumed to be spatially constant
## throughout all geometries
mapview(tuls_hs)

Making a static map

#install.packages("ggmap")
library(ggmap)
library(viridis)
## Warning: package 'viridis' was built under R version 3.4.3
## Loading required package: viridisLite
## Warning: package 'viridisLite' was built under R version 3.4.3
map1 <- get_map(location = c(-118.302, 36.22),#x = lon, #y = lat
               color = "bw", 
               maptype = "terrain",
               source = "google",
               zoom = 8)
## Map from URL : http://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/staticmap?center=36.22,-118.302&zoom=8&size=640x640&scale=2&maptype=terrain&language=en-EN&sensor=false
ggmap(map1)+
  geom_sf(data = tuls_hs, aes(color = Temp_F), size = 3, shape = 16, inherit.aes = FALSE)+
  scale_color_viridis(option = "inferno")
## Coordinate system already present. Adding new coordinate system, which will replace the existing one.
